 &lt;p&gt;As well as being able to change the class associated with an element or a set of elements on a screen, jQuery also allows you to fire events.  You might want to do this, for example, if you want to simulate the clicking of a button. Of course, if you are going to fire an event, you’ll probably need some sort of event listener setup to handle that. We will address firing events first since it has the least amount of code needed. All you need to do is select the element or elements using the selectors we’ve already discussed and then call the method trigger(‘eventname’). So, to click a button, your code might look something like this:&lt;/p&gt;
